Hold Left Click to Attack
Hold Right Click to Dash

To Dad:


Ive been distant from you since the day you and Mom separated. Its not that I dont want to be with you; its justevery time youre aroundit reminds me of that day. I thought over time that maybe it would stop hurting; I never realized that time only exacerbates the pain. Theres nothing I want more than to reach out to you for help because I dont think I can do this alone. I just dont have the courage. People say journaling helps, so Im giving it a shot. Funny, I used to paint for the same reason. But even my favorite hobby reminds me of the pain of Mom leaving. So, for now, Ill write. Perhaps this will be what I need to come out of my shell.


Lets start from the beginning: one day, when I was walking home from school. It was a Tuesday, so I knew both you and Mom were home. I thought maybe we could do something as a family, like painting. Okay, it was more like you guys would watch me paint while you watch your dramas. When I approached the front door, I heard your voice. It wasnt the happy inflections I was used to hearing. I didnt know what to do, so I just stood there and listened.

But that wasnt the only fight I heard. First, the clothes and accessories Mom thought would look great on her growing nieces and nephews. Then the lottery ticket in her purse. Then the broken sink she thought she could fix. Every other night, your loud, angry whispers echoed through the halls of our tiny home. You didnt know that I could still hear you. You also didnt know that as I lay on my bed, tears rolled down my eyes like rain on a stormy day. I wanted nothing more than to storm outside my room and tell you both to shut up and get along. But I couldnt. So I pretended that none of it was happening. Everything is okay, Dad is just busy today, I told myself, Hell be home to paint with me next week.


Weeks became months. I was sick of pretending everything was okay. I needed someone to blame. So I blamed you. You were always busy working late shifts. Mom, on the other hand, was there for me every day. I would paint, while she struggles to make a circle. There would be laughter. Hollow laughter. Every Tuesday you spent working was like a bullet to my heart. It was so easy to blame you because you werent there for me like Mom was. It was so easy, even though you didnt deserve blame.

You eventually did get me that paint set like you promised, not that it matters anymore. I knew our family was falling apart. Every other night becomes every night. Every little thing spirals into contempt. A glass of water at night turns into a perilous journey through the cracks of this broken home. Sometimes, I just have to be so careful to not trip and fall into the darkness. Because if I did, who would be there to glue the pieces together? Not you. Not Mom. Just me.


So I did what I could only think to do. I opened the paint set and began painting. There was a memory that I like to recall when things get rough. I thought it would remind us of a time when we could all hold hands and laugh. And I thought it would turn back time to when everything was truly alright. You and Mom would finally get along once again. But I was too late.

I never showed you the painting, so I bet youre wondering what it's about. Do you remember when you and Mom took me on that hike? With my little legs, it felt like we were walking around the earth. I would pester you with Are we there yet? until you gave up and started carrying me.


Were almost there, you replied, I dont know why youre complaining, youre not doing any walking!


Youre too slow Daddy! I would say as I shook you, Faster! Faster!


I could carry him if you want! Mom offered as she laughed. Eventually, we made it to the end of the trail. We were on a cliff, overlooking a lush, green field bathed in the warm, orange light of the setting sun. We all had a seat on the gravel floor. I was tucked away in your lap, while Mom rested her head on your shoulder. We admired the view for what seemed to be an eternity too short.


Sometimes when I feel like Im all alone in the world, I use this memory to remind me that I can always talk to you or Mom. Its why I decided to paint it. Dad, I dont want to keep pushing you away. Sometimes, it's just hard to look past all the self-doubt, the false narrative I put into every memory when I give in to my fears. I hope you understand.

Was it all a lie? What about that time we hiked for hours up that mountain to see the sunset? You were never happy together, but you mask your contempt with laughter and lies. You told me that we would be together forever. Mom said she would be back. Its been years now, so where is she?


But I get it. You both lied to protect me. You didnt want to juxtapose your child with a broken home. Most importantly, you didnt want me to know that it was my fault for failing to keep things together. Perhaps, if I had never asked for those stupid paintbrushes and acrylics in the first place, we would still be together. 


This is stupid. Why do I even bother? Journaling is not gonna fix this family. Its a waste of time, just like my painting.
